This paper deals with the implementation of a fundamental synchronization primitive in shared memory systems, which falls under the category of distributed computing (cs.DC). The paper also involves the study of lower and upper bounds on the number of registers required for the implementation, which is related to data structures (cs.DS) and programming languages (cs.PL). The paper also discusses the transformation of deterministic algorithms into randomized ones, which is a topic in theoretical computer science (cs.TH) and systems and control (cs.SY). Finally, the paper involves the study of wait-free algorithms, which is a subfield of distributed computing (cs.DC) and logic in computer science (cs.LO).
